      <!-- Section 1: What Is Generative Search -->
      <div class="prose-dark">
        <h2 id="what-is-generative-search" class="anchor-top">What Is Generative Search?</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>Generative search is a mode of information retrieval in which AI systems synthesise an answer from multiple sources and present it directly to the user, rather than returning a ranked list of links.</strong> Instead of clicking through ten blue links to find an answer, the user receives a generated response — typically a paragraph or structured summary — that draws on information from several web sources, with optional citations to the contributing pages.
        </p>
        <p>
          Generative search began displacing traditional results in earnest in 2023, with Google's rollout of AI Overviews (formerly Search Generative Experience) and the launch of Perplexity AI as a standalone search product. By 2026, AI-generated answers appear for a significant and growing proportion of Google queries, and dedicated AI search engines have established tens of millions of regular users. The shift is structural, not cyclical.
        </p>
        <p>
          For the brand or organisation that depends on organic search visibility, generative search changes the competitive dynamic fundamentally. Traditional search allocates ten positions on page one. A generative answer typically cites two to five sources. Brands that earn those citations receive attention, trust, and referral traffic. Brands that are absent from AI answers are invisible to a growing share of users — even users who are actively searching for exactly what those brands offer.
        </p>
        <p>
          Generative search optimisation addresses this shift directly. It is the discipline of aligning content, entity signals, and technical infrastructure with the selection criteria that AI search systems use when deciding which sources to retrieve, synthesise, and cite. For a detailed technical breakdown of how this selection process works, see our guide on <a href="/how-geo-works/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">how GEO works</a>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section 2: The Key Surfaces -->
      <div class="prose-dark mt-16">
        <h2 id="the-key-surfaces" class="anchor-top">The Key AI Search Surfaces</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>Generative search optimisation targets five primary platforms, each with a distinct architecture and retrieval model — and a complete strategy accounts for all five rather than optimising for one in isolation.</strong>
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="mt-8 overflow-x-auto rounded-xl border hair">
        <table class="w-full text-sm">
          <thead>
            <tr class="border-b hair bg-white/[.03]">
              <th scope="col" class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-white">Platform</th>
              <th scope="col" class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-white">Retrieval Mechanism</th>
              <th scope="col" class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-white">Key Optimisation Signal</th>
              <th scope="col" class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-white">Priority</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="divide-y hair">
            {surfaces.map(s => (
              <tr class="transition hover:bg-white/[.02]">
                <td class="px-4 py-3 font-semibold text-white">{s.name}</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">{s.mechanism}</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">{s.keySignal}</td>
                <td class="px-4 py-3 text-ink-300">{s.priority}</td>
              </tr>
            ))}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <div class="prose-dark mt-8">
        <h3>Google AI Overviews</h3>
        <p>
          Google AI Overviews is the most consequential generative search surface for most brands because it appears on the world's highest-traffic search engine. AI Overviews synthesise answers from multiple web sources and display them at the top of Google results, above the traditional organic listings. The retrieval model draws heavily from pages that already perform well in Google's organic index, meaning traditional SEO authority is a prerequisite for AI Overview inclusion — but entity schema and content structure determine which high-ranking pages are actually cited.
        </p>

        <h3>ChatGPT Search</h3>
        <p>
          ChatGPT's search mode (available to ChatGPT users globally) combines OpenAI's language model with live web retrieval via Bing's index. When a query triggers a search, the system fetches current web content and synthesises a response with cited sources. Brands that appear in Bing's index and have strong entity signals in both training-data corpora and live web content are most consistently cited. The same optimisation work that targets Copilot (Bing-indexed content, Bing Webmaster Tools verification) transfers directly to ChatGPT Search.
        </p>

        <h3>Perplexity AI</h3>
        <p>
          Perplexity operates as a dedicated AI search engine with its own web crawler (PerplexityBot) and a pure RAG architecture: every query triggers a live web fetch, and the answer is assembled entirely from retrieved content with explicit source citations. This makes Perplexity the most transparent platform for testing generative search visibility. If your content earns citation on Perplexity, the extraction architecture is working. Allow PerplexityBot in robots.txt, keep dateModified current in schema, and structure content for clean passage extraction.
        </p>

        <h3>Microsoft Copilot</h3>
        <p>
          Copilot is integrated across Bing, Microsoft Edge, and Microsoft 365. It uses Bing's web index as its retrieval layer, making Bing SEO directly relevant to Copilot citation. Verify your site in Bing Webmaster Tools, submit your sitemap to Bing, and confirm Bingbot is allowed in robots.txt. Copilot's integration with workplace tools means it is increasingly relevant for B2B brands whose target audience uses Microsoft 365 for research.
        </p>

        <h3>Gemini</h3>
        <p>
          Google's Gemini conversational AI is integrated with Google Search and available as a standalone product. Like Google AI Overviews, Gemini's web-grounded responses draw from Google's index. The optimisation signals overlap substantially: entity clarity, E-E-A-T, structured data, and strong organic authority. As Gemini expands its integration with Google Workspace, it will become increasingly relevant for professional and enterprise search behaviour.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section 3: How AI Results Are Selected -->
      <div class="prose-dark mt-16">
        <h2 id="how-generative-search-selects" class="anchor-top">How AI Search Results Are Selected</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>Every generative search platform selects sources through a multi-stage process — and failing at any single stage means earning no citation, regardless of content quality.</strong> The selection pipeline consists of four stages: indexation (was your content discovered and stored?), retrieval (was your page selected as a candidate for this query?), synthesis (was your content extracted into the generated answer?), and citation (was your source attributed credit for the response?).
        </p>
        <p>
          Each stage applies different criteria. Indexation depends on crawler access and technical accessibility. Retrieval depends on topical relevance and entity clarity. Synthesis depends on content structure and passage extractability. Citation depends on entity authority, schema signals, and the uniqueness of your information contribution. A comprehensive generative search optimisation strategy addresses all four stages rather than treating the problem as a single-lever optimisation.
        </p>
        <p>
          For a complete stage-by-stage technical breakdown of this pipeline, including specific tactics for each stage, see our dedicated guide: <a href="/how-geo-works/" class="text-accent-400 underline decoration-accent-500/30 underline-offset-2 hover:text-accent-300">how generative engine optimisation works</a>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section 4: Optimisation Tactics -->
      <div class="prose-dark mt-16">
        <h2 id="optimisation-tactics" class="anchor-top">Optimisation Tactics for Generative Search</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>Effective generative search optimisation combines entity authority, extractable content structure, technical accessibility, and active measurement — applied consistently across all target platforms.</strong>
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="mt-8 space-y-4">
        {tactics.map(t => (
          <div class="card p-6 flex gap-5">
            <span class="font-mono text-sm font-bold text-[var(--accent)] flex-shrink-0 pt-0.5">{t.step}</span>
            <div>
              <h3 class="font-display text-base font-semibold text-white mb-2">{t.title}</h3>
